# Fastify route authoring

`apps/api` is a Fastify app. HTTP handlers live under
`apps/api/src/routes/**`, async processors under
`apps/api/src/workers/**`, scheduled jobs under `apps/api/src/cron/**`.
Deep-dive: `.cursor/skills/fastify-routes/SKILL.md`. Pairs with
`.cursor/rules/wide-event-logging.mdc`.

## Route file shape

Every route file default-exports a `FastifyPluginAsync` and registers
exactly one URL. `server.ts` mounts all of them via `routes/index.ts`.

```ts
import type { FastifyPluginAsync } from 'fastify'
import type { ZodTypeProvider } from 'fastify-type-provider-zod'

const route: FastifyPluginAsync = async (app) => {
  app.withTypeProvider<ZodTypeProvider>().post(
    '/api/v1/thing',
    { schema: { body: BodySchema, response: { 200: OkSchema } } },
    async (req, reply) => { /* ... */ },
  )
}

export default route
```

- Always `.withTypeProvider<ZodTypeProvider>()` when using Zod schemas
  in `schema`; otherwise request params are untyped.
- Keep one route per file; register it in `routes/index.ts`.
- HTTP methods that mutate must declare `body` in `schema`; Fastify +
  the Zod provider will 400 on invalid input automatically.

## Plugin / middleware order

Registered globally in `server.ts` (don't re-register per-route):

```
securityHeaders -> rateLimiter -> apiKeyAuth -> wideEvent
```

- `apiKeyAuth` is a `preHandler` that bypasses `/api/v1/health` and
  accepts `?api_key=...` only under `/docs/**` (for Swagger UI).
- `wideEvent` is **always last** so it observes the final status code.
- Webhook routes opt in to `fastify-raw-body` via route-level config
  (`config: { rawBody: true }`) and verify HMAC inside the handler
  using `req.rawBody`.

## Schemas

- `body: SomeZodSchema` / `querystring: SomeZodSchema` /
  `params: SomeZodSchema` are validated by the Zod provider. `req.body`
  / `req.query` / `req.params` are typed from the schema.
- `response: { 200: OutputSchema }` enables response serialization.
  Omit when Convex widens a type and would break the handler return;
  the canonical contract still lives in `@carrier-sales/shared`.
- Never `as any` to force a schema through. If there's a v3/v4 mismatch,
  use `asStepSchema` from `apps/api/src/lib/zod-schema.ts` (the single
  audited bridge).

## Response bodies

Non-2xx bodies must be `{ error, message, statusCode }`:

```ts
return reply.code(404).send({
  error: 'Not Found',
  message: `Load ${load_id} not found`,
  statusCode: 404,
})
```

Never `throw` for expected 4xx -- use `reply.code(...).send(...)`.
Unexpected errors propagate to the global error handler in `server.ts`,
which maps to a 500 with the same shape.

## Observability

- HTTP routes: call `enrichWideEvent(req, { ... })` at every meaningful
  branch. The `wideEvent` plugin emits the canonical log on response.
- Queue workers / cron jobs: wrap the whole handler in
  `withWideEvent('Name', { logger, seed }, async (enrich) => { ... })`
  -- never mix patterns.
- In every `catch`, add `enrichWideEvent(req, { failure_stage: '...' })`
  (routes) or `enrich({ failure_stage: '...' })` (workers / cron)
  before returning 5xx / rethrowing.
- Metric attributes stay LOW cardinality (`outcome`, `result`, `round`
  as string). High-cardinality fields (`call_id`, `load_id`,
  `mc_number`) go on the wide event. See `wide-event-logging.mdc`.

## Enqueues

- Topics live in `QUEUE_NAMES` in `apps/api/src/queues/index.ts`. Input
  schemas (`ClassifyCallInputSchema`, ...) are the contract between
  producer and worker.
- Producer: `await classifyCallQueue.add(QUEUE_NAMES.classifyCall, data)`.
- Consumer: `new Worker(QUEUE_NAMES.classifyCall, handler, { connection })`
  with `Schema.parse(job.data)` at the top of the handler.

## Don'ts

- No raw `console.log` -- use `req.log.*` (routes) or `logger.*`
  (workers / cron).
- No second canonical `logger.info` line per request -- the wide event
  is the canonical log.
- No `z.date()` anywhere; timestamps are ISO `string`.
- No raw Zod schema cast with `as any` to satisfy a response schema.
